The Operator shall have a management system that ensures:

	(i) Management of safety and security in flight operations;

	(ii) Supervision and control of all flights, operational control functions and other associate ctivities;

	(iii) Compliance with standards of the Operator and requirements of the State of the Operator
(hereinafter, the State) and other applicable authorities.

The Operator shall ensure the management system for operational control defines the safet ccountability, authorities and responsibilities of management and non-management personnel tha erform functions relevant to the operational control of flights. The management system shall als pecify:

	(i) The levels of management with the authority to make decisions regarding risk tolerabilit ith respect to the safety and/or security of aircraft operations;

	(ii) Responsibilities for ensuring operational control is conducted in accordance with applicabl egulations and standards of the Operator;

	(iii) Lines of safety accountability within the organization, including direct accountability fo afety and/or security on the part of operational control senior management.

The Operator shall ensure accountability, authorities and responsibilities for the operational control o lights are defined and communicated throughout the organization, to include the authorities an esponsibilities of the pilot-in command (PIC) and, as applicable, the:

	(i) Flight operations officer (FOO), who supports, briefs and/or assists the PIC or designate ember of management regarding risk tolerability with respect to the safe conduct of eac light;

	(ii) Designated member of management or post holder that has joint authority with the PIC ove he decision functions, duties or tasks associated with the operational control of each flight;

	(iii) Flight operations assistant (FOA) who supports, briefs and/or assists the PIC, FOO, o esignated member of management in the safe conduct of each flight.

The Operator shall have a process or procedures for the delegation of duties within the managemen ystem for operational control that ensures managerial and operational control continuity i aintained and responsibility for operational control functions is assumed by qualified personne hen:

	(i) Managers directly responsible for the operational control of flights are unable to carry ou ork duties;

	(ii) If used in the system of operational control, FOO and/or FOA personnel are unable to carr ut work duties.

If an FOO is used in the system of operational control, the Operator shall assign responsibility to suc ersonnel for:

	(i) Assisting the PIC in flight preparation and providing required information;

	(ii) Assisting the PIC in preparing the operational and ATS flight plans;

	(iii) When applicable, signing the operational and ATS flight plans;

	(iv) Filing the ATS flight plan with the appropriate ATS unit;

	(v) Furnishing the PIC, while in flight, with appropriate information necessary for the saf onduct of the flight;

	(vi) If the Operator tracks aircraft position in accordance with DSP 3.5.2 and/or DSP 3.5.3,
notifying the appropriate ATS unit when the position of the aircraft cannot be determined b n aircraft tracking capability, and attempts to establish communication are unsuccessful;

	(vii) In the event of an emergency, initiating relevant procedures as specified in the OM.

The Operator shall have a process to be used in the event of an emergency situation that endanger he safety of the aircraft or persons, including those situations that become known first to th perator. Such process shall ensure the FOO, FOA or other delegated person:

	(i) Initiates emergency procedures, as outlined in the OM, while avoiding taking any action tha ould conflict with ATC procedures;

	(ii) Notifies the appropriate authorities, without delay, of the nature of the situation;

	(iii) Requests assistance, if required;

	(iv) Conveys, by any available means, safety-related information to the PIC that may b ecessary for the safe conduct of the flight, including information related to any necessar mendments to the flight plan.

The Operator shall have a system that enables effective communication of relevant safety an perational information throughout the operational control management system and in all area here operational control is conducted. Such system shall ensure:

	(i) Personnel maintain an awareness of the SMS;

	(ii) Safety-critical information is conveyed;

	(iii) If applicable, external service providers are provided with information relevant to operation onducted.

The Operator shall have a communication system that ensures operational control personnel ar rovided with or have access to information relevant to the safe conduct of each flight, to includ nformation associated with:

	(i) The aircraft (MEL, maintenance);

	(ii) Meteorology;

	(iii) Safety, including current accident and incident notification procedures;

	(iv) Routes, including over water and critical terrain (NOTAMs, facilities, outages);

	(v) Air Traffic Services (ATS).

If an FOO is used in the system of operational control, the Operator should ensure personnel hired t erform the FOO functions are not less than 21 years of age and meet one or more of the followin riteria:

	(i) Have, as a minimum, one year of experience as an assistant in the operational control of ai ransport flights, or

	(ii) Have satisfactorily completed a formal training course as a flight operations officer or fligh ispatcher, or

	(iii) Have, as a minimum, a total of two years of service in any one or combination of th ollowing:

		(a) Flight crew member in air transport operations;

		(b) Meteorologist in an organization dispatching aircraft;

		(c) Air traffic controller;

		(d) Technical supervisor of FOO personnel;

		(e) Technical supervisor of air transportation systems.

If an FOO or FOA is used in the system of operational control, the Operator shall have a process t nsure such personnel, prior to being assigned duties in an operational control function:

	(i) As applicable, meet minimum age, knowledge, experience and skill requirements of th tate;

	(ii) Are trained to a minimum competency level acceptable to the Operator and/or State;

	(iii) For FOAs, have demonstrated the ability to provide assistance in their area(s) o ompetency to, as applicable, the PIC and/or FOO.

The Operator shall have a system for the management and control of documentation and/or dat sed directly in the conduct or support of Dispatch operations. Such system shall ensur ocumentation:

	(i) Meets all required elements specified in Table 1.1 ;

	(ii) Contains legible and accurate information;

	(iii) Is presented in a format appropriate for use in operations.

The Operator shall ensure the system for the management and control of operational contro ocumentation as specified in ORG 2.5.1 andTable 1.1 addresses, as a minimum, the followin ocuments from external sources:

	(i) As applicable, regulations of the State of the Operator and of other states or authoritie elevant to operations;

	(ii) As applicable, ICAO Standards and Recommended Practices; (SARPS), manuals, regiona upplementary procedures and/or circulars;

	(iii) Airworthiness Directives (ADs);

	(iv) As applicable, Aeronautical Information Publications, (AIP) and NOTAMS;

	(v) State-approved or State-Accepted Aircraft Flight Manuals (AFM);

	(vi) Manufacturer's Aircraft Operating Manuals (AOMs), including performance data, weight an alance data/manuals, checklists and MEL/CDL;

	(vii) As applicable, other manufacturer's operational communications.

The Operator shall have an Operations Manual (OM) for the use of operational control personnel,
which may be issued in separate parts, and which contains or references the policies, procedure nd other guidance or information necessary for compliance with applicable regulations, laws, rule nd Operator standards. As a minimum, the OM shall:

	(i) Be managed and controlled in accordance with DSP 1.6.1;

	(ii) Have all parts relevant to operational control personnel clearly identified and defined;

	(iii) Be in accordance with the specifications in Table 3.2 .

The Operator shall have a description of the Operational Flight Plan (OFP) or equivalent documen hat is published in the OM and includes:

	(i) Guidance for use by operational control personnel;

	(ii) An outline of the content in accordance with specifications in Table 3.3 .

The Operator shall have a system for the management and control of operational control records t nsure the content and retention of such records is in accordance with requirements of the Authority,
as applicable, and to ensure operational records are subjected to standardized processes for:

	(i) Identification;

	(ii) Legibility;

	(iii) Maintenance;

	(iv) Retention and retrieval;

	(v) Protection, integrity and security;

	(vi) Disposal, deletion (electronic records) and archiving.

The Operator shall ensure the system for the management and control of operational control record s specified in DSP 1.8.1 addresses, as a minimum, records that document or include:

	(i) Operational information, communications and data for each flight specified in DSP 1.8.4 an able 3.4 ;

	(ii) The fulfillment of FOO and/or FOA qualification requirements specified in DSP 1.8.6 ,1.8. nd1.8.9 , as applicable;

	(iii) A signed copy of the OFP or equivalent document, as specified in DSP 3.2.5 .

If an FOO or FOA is used in the system of operational control, the Operator shall ensure trainin ecords for such personnel, as applicable, are managed and maintained in accordance wit SP 1.8.1 , to include records that document completion of:

	(i) Initial qualification;

	(ii) Continuing qualification;

	(iii) Competency evaluations.

The Operator shall have a quality assurance program that provides for the auditing and evaluation o he management system and operational control functions at planned intervals to ensure th rganization(s) with responsibility for operational control is (are):

	(i) Complying with applicable regulations and standards;

	(ii) Satisfying stated operational control needs;

	(iii) Identifying areas requiring improvement;

	(iv) Identifying hazards to operations;

	(v) Assessing the effectiveness of safety risk controls.

The Operator shall have an audit planning process and sufficient resources to ensure audits o perational control functions are:

	(i) Scheduled at intervals to meet regulatory and management system requirements;

	(ii) Conducted within the scheduled interval.

The Operator shall have a process for addressing findings that result from audits conducted unde he quality assurance program, which ensures:

	(i) Identification of root cause(s);

	(ii) Development of corrective action as appropriate to address findings;

	(iii) Implementation of corrective action in appropriate operational areas;

	(iv) Evaluation of corrective action to determine effectiveness.

If the Operator has external service providers conduct outsourced operational control functions, th perator should ensure a service provider selection process is in place that ensures:

	(i) Relevant safety and security selection criteria are established;

	(ii) Service providers are evaluated against such criteria prior to selection.

If the Operator uses electronic navigation data products for application in operational control, th perator shall have processes, approved or accepted by the State, if required, which ensure suc lectronic navigation data products acquired from suppliers, prior to being used in operations:

	(i) Are assessed for a level of data integrity commensurate with the intended application;

	(ii) Are compatible with the intended function of equipment in which it is installed.

The Operator shall have a safety risk assessment and mitigation program in the organizatio esponsible for the operational control of flights that specifies processes to ensure:

	(i) Hazards are analyzed to determine the corresponding safety risks to aircraft operations;

	(ii) Safety risks are assessed to determine the requirement for risk mitigation action(s);

	(iii) When required, risk mitigation actions are developed and implemented in operationa ontrol.

The Operator shall have an operational safety reporting system in the organization responsible fo he operational control of flights that:

	(i) Encourages and facilitates operational control personnel to submit reports that identif afety hazards, expose safety deficiencies and raise safety concerns;

	(ii) Ensures mandatory reporting in accordance with applicable regulations;

	(iii) Includes analysis and operational control management action as necessary to addres afety issues identified through the reporting system.

If an FOO, FOA or designated member of management is used in the system of operational control,
the Operator shall have a line qualification program to ensure such personnel, prior to being assigne o operational control duties, have demonstrated proficiency in the competencies of operationa ontrol as specified in Table 3.5 , as applicable to the Operator, and have demonstrated the ability to:

	(i) Assist the PIC in flight preparation and provide the relevant information required;

	(ii) File a flight plan with the appropriate ATS unit;

	(iii) Furnish the PIC in flight, by appropriate means, with information that may be necessary fo he safe conduct of the flight;

	(iv) Initiate, in the event of an emergency, applicable procedures as outlined in the OM.

The Operator shall have guidance and procedures that ensure the original OFP or equivalen ocument is accepted and signed by the following personnel, using either manuscript or an approve lectronic method:

	(i) The PIC for all systems of operational control;

	(ii) The FOO for a shared system of operational control;

	(iii) Designated member of management or post holder in a shared system of operationa ontrol that requires the use of such management personnel.

If an FOO is used in a full shared system of operational control, the Operator shall have guidanc nd procedures to ensure en route amendments to the OFP are coordinated and verified through:

	(i) A signature (manuscript or approved electronic method) by the FOO or other perso esponsible for operational control;

	(ii) A recorded agreement of the PIC.

If the Operator is authorized to conduct certain portions of a commercial flight under visual flight rules(VFR), the Operator shall have guidance and procedures that:

	(i) Specify the type of flight plan to be filed with the appropriate ATS unit;

	(ii) Require current meteorological reports, or a combination of current reports and forecasts, t ndicate that meteorological conditions along the portion of the flight to be flown under VF ill, at the appropriate time, be such as to make compliance with VFR possible.

The Operator shall have guidance and procedures to ensure a planned flight does not exceed:

	(i) The maximum performance takeoff, en route and landing weight limits, based upo nvironmental conditions expected at the times of departure, along the route of flight and a rrival;

	(ii) The aircraft structural ramp, takeoff and landing weight limits.

If the Operator conducts flights from any airport when conditions are conducive to ground aircraf cing, the Operator shall have guidance and procedures to ensure a flight planned to operate i nown or suspected ground icing conditions is subjected to the following:

	(i) The aircraft has been inspected for ice accretion;

	(ii) If necessary, the aircraft has been given appropriate de/anti-icing treatment.

If an FOO or FOA is used in a shared system of operational control, the Operator shall hav rocedures and equipment that ensure effective communication between the:

	(i) FOO and the PIC;

	(ii) If applicable, FOA and the PIC;

	(iii) FOO, PIC and maintenance.

If the Operator conducts international flights with aircraft that have emergency and surviva quipment on board, the Operator shall ensure the availability of information for immediat ommunication to rescue coordination centers that describes such equipment, to include, a pplicable:

	(i) The number, color and type of lifesaving rafts and pyrotechnics;

	(ii) Details of emergency medical and water supplies;

	(iii) Type and frequencies of the emergency portable radio equipment.

The Operator shall have guidance and procedures to ensure FOO, FOA or other designate ersonnel:

	(i) Notify the appropriate authority in the quickest manner of any accident involving an aircraf hat results in a fatal or serious injury to any person or substantial damage to the aircraft o roperty;

	(ii) Make position information of a flight in distress available to the appropriate organizations a stablished by the State.

If the Operator transports dangerous goods as cargo, the Operator shall ensure FOO, FOA and/o ther designated operational control personnel:

	(i) Have access to the same information pertaining to dangerous goods carried as cargo o oard the aircraft that is provided to the PIC;

	(ii) Are assigned the responsibility to provide detailed information without delay abou angerous goods carried as cargo to emergency services responding to an accident o erious incident involving the Operator's aircraft.

If the Operator conducts isolated airport operations that preclude the selection of any destinatio lternate airport in accordance with DSP 4.1.4 or4.1.5 , the Operator shall have a process to ensure,
for each flight into an isolated destination airport:

	(i) The designation of a point of safe return (PSR);

	(ii) The flight does not continue past the PSR unless a current assessment of meteorologica onditions, traffic, and other operational conditions indicate that a safe landing can be mad t the ETU.

If the Operator uses aircraft with three or more engines, the Operator shall have guidance an rocedures for diversion planning and the provision of an OFP that ensures aircraft with three o ore engines can either:

	(i) If a second engine becomes inoperative en route, continue from the point where tw ngines are assumed to fail simultaneously to an en route alternate airport at which th anding distance specification for alternate airports is complied with and where it is expecte hat a safe landing can be made, or

	(ii) If a single engine becomes inoperative en route, and for operations conducted in areas o he world with limited diversion options, the flight is planned with a more distant alternat han specified in item i) in order to provide for a diversion for any en route contingency tha ay limit the planned operation. Such diversion planning shall be conducted in accordanc ith the specifications of a program approved or accepted by the State that requires th perator to actively manage the risk of subsequent engine failures or other flight limitin ccurrences and:

		(a) Contains special considerations for extended range flights conducted over remot reas designed to prevent the need for a diversion and protect the diversion to a lternate airport when it cannot be prevented;

		(b) Uses aircraft designed and manufactured for the intended operation and maintaine o ensure original reliability;

		(c) Requires the Operator to implement and maintain a problem reporting, tracking an esolution system that contains a means for the prompt reporting, tracking an esolution of specific problems, as designated by the Operator or State, that coul ffect the safety of the operation;

		(d) Requires a prescribed level of engine reliability, as measured by an in-fligh hutdown rate (IFSD) determined by the Operator or State, where the risk o ndependent failures leading to a loss of thrust from two simultaneous engin ailures ceases to limit the operation and other limiting factors come into play;

		(e) Designates a maximum diversion distance in cases where a diversion is necessar or any reason, including limiting airframe systems and reasons that do not hav nything to do with aircraft reliability, such as passenger illness;

		(f) Requires the Operator to demonstrate to the applicable authorities that, whe onsidering the impact of increasing diversion time, the operation can be conducte t a level of reliability which maintains an acceptable level of risk. [PCO]

The Operator shall have a system, process and/or procedures to ensure the amount of usable fuel t e carried on an aircraft in accordance with DSP 4.3.1 is, as a minimum, based on the following dat nd operating conditions for each planned flight:

	(i) Current aircraft-specific data derived from a fuel consumption monitoring program, i vailable, or if current aircraft-specific data is not available, data provided by the aircraf anufacturer;

	(ii) The anticipated aircraft mass;

	(iii) Notices to Airmen (NOTAM);

	(iv) Current meteorological reports, or a combination of current reports and forecasts;

	(v) Applicable air traffic services procedures, restrictions and anticipated delays;

	(vi) The effects of deferred maintenance items and/or configuration deviations;

	(vii) Any other conditions that might cause increased fuel consumption.

The Operator shall have a process and/or procedures to ensure, for flights that require a singl estination alternate airport, the destination alternate fuel required in accordance with its fuel policy i ot lower than amount of fuel that will enable the aircraft to complete all of the following:

	(i) Perform a missed approach at the destination airport;

	(ii) Climb to the expected cruising altitude;

	(iii) Fly the expected routing to the destination alternate airport;

	(iv) Descend to the point where the expected approach is initiated;

	(v) Conduct the approach and landing at the destination alternate airport.

If the Operator conducts flight operations beyond 60 minutes from a point on a route to an en rout lternate airport, including ETOPS/EDTO, the Operator shall have guidance and procedures t nsure (as applicable to the Operator):

	(i) For all aircraft, en route alternate airports are identified and the most up-to-date informatio elative to such airports is available to the flight crew, including airport status an eteorological conditions;

	(ii) For aircraft with two engines engaged in ETOPS/EDTO, the most up-to-date informatio vailable to the flight crew indicates that conditions at identified en route alternate airport ill be at or above the Operator's established airport operating minima for the operation a he ETU.

If the Operator uses aircraft with two engines in ETOPS/EDTO, the Operator shall have guidanc nd procedures to select en route alternate airports for such operations, and ensure en rout lternate airports are specified on:

	(i) The OFP or other equivalent operational document available to the PIC in flight;

	(ii) The ATS flight plan where required by the State or the ATS system in use.

If the Operator conducts ETOPS/EDTO, the Operator shall have guidance and procedures to ensure,
for aircraft engaged in such operations:

	(i) A flight will not proceed beyond the threshold time unless the identified en route alternat irports are re-evaluated for availability and the most up-to-date information indicates that,
during the ETU, conditions at those airports will be at or above the Operator's establishe irport operating minima for the operation;

	(ii) If any conditions are identified that would preclude a safe approach and landing at a dentified en route alternate airport during the ETU, an alternative course of action has bee etermined;

	(iii) The most limiting EDTO-significant system time limitation (except for the most limiting fir uppression system), if any, indicated in the aircraft flight manual (directly or by reference)
and relevant to a particular operation is not exceeded.
